title: Anet A8 Y-Axis Idler & Motor Brace Upgrades
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: These braces represent my attempt at improving some of the already excellent Anet A8 parts provided here on Thingiverse. The braces I have seen previously have some features that make using several of the belt tensioner upgrades difficult to impossible. You can see in some of my photos that it was an iterative process for me as I had to file some grooves out of the idler brace gussets to provide clearance for installing the required hardware. The models that have been uploaded have been revised to reflect what I learned. My goal was to design these in such a way as so they could be printed with little to no support material. I chose to use support material when printing the parts shown in the photos for cleaner surfaces. The supports were easy to remove and left clean features. I also wanted to provide a way to fasten the machine down to a rigid structure to prevent movement or misalignment of the printers frame. The holes provided were sized for common #10 wood screws as I plan to use MDF as a base. Another aspect of the idler brace is that it completely replaces the original component, rather than being installed in front of the original, and consequently does not reduce the y-axis travel distance as with previous designs. I also tried to keep aesthetics in mind when designing these and my final goal was improve the rudimentary features from previous designs. So many of the free or open source modeling packages limit the level of refinement designers can bring to their models. I hope these help everyone make the most out of the best cheap 3D printer around. Enjoy!

comments.text: I have considered designing a total rebuild of the stock frame as it lacks many features and isn't as rigid or robust as it could be. My main goal with these designs was to add sufficient rigidity to the stock frame, using as little material as possible, to keep cost and print time to a minimum for other A8 users. In conjunction with this designs gussets, using the provided fastener holes to mount the entire machine to a stable surface, being sure to do so without binding the frame, will improve print quality as well as reduce machine noise and vibration. I didn't see any advantage, mechanically or aesthetically, to incorporating the y-axis motor bracket into my components. Although it is certainly possible.

title: Contour camera mounts - one sided for helmet, flat and curved surfaces

description.text:
Wanted something that would allow flush mounting for a helmet or curved surface or as a base to make others.   
Made it long enough so that double sided 3M tape could be used and ensure you have plenty of surface area.   
Mounts are for the left side of the camera (looking toward the shooting direction of the camera). If you want right side - invert the image before slicing I guess.  
Pick how curved you want from the HIGH, MEDIUM, LOW or FLAT.   
Pictures are of the HIGH and the FLAT versions. So you can see the HIGH is pretty full-on, probably not useful for much.  
Let me know if you nee other variations or any mods to the design that might be useful.
Printed with standard medium settings on replicator 2. If think it is going to get an absolute battering - maybe increase the infill amount and/or shells.

description.text:
This part may not help too many others (if any) but it has served me well. My wife's dish rack broke and my 3D printer came to the rescue. I know this is a cheap dish rack that isn't worth rescuing but it would just add to the world's landfills. With a very inexpensive part, $0.16 (estimated), and a little effort, the dish rack was put back into service.

This part showcases the real world application of 3D printers.

I basically created a cast, (not out of plaster but rather in PLA) for the broken arm. I sized it 101% of the actual size and it fit perfectly. In fact, I didn't even glue the broken part because it's holding so well. As you can tell from the picture, I didn't print the part ideally to maximize strength but it has been holding up well. Should it ever break/fail, I will reprint it with a different orientation to maximize part strength.

Hail to 3D printers and all the useful things they make!

comments.text: Ah yes, trimming off support material can be quite a doozie. I found that the best way to remove it from this piece is to first start with the legs by clipping the areas of the raft between the paws and support blocks (you may use a fine pair of wire cutters or a sharp xacto knife), you will also want to cut any other thin strands of plastic bonded to the legs. This will prevent you from pulling off a leg after you break free the main supports. Once the supports are free of the legs and any other support block if possible, start with the tail and firmly grab both the bulk of the tail and its respective support piece. Then carefully work them free of each other, it should be a clean break. Next you will want to repeat this with the head then the torso. Don't worry if you break off a leg or four, I did, and a few drops of supper glue made it look like it never even happened. Once all that is done, it may be wise to use an xacto knife to remove any pesky drips or burrs. That's it, I hope this helped.

This is a remix of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1172838 and http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:102482

printer: Anet A8 (customized)
slicer: Simplify3D
infill: 30% (fast honeycomb)
supports: none
wall layers: 4

speed 100mm/s

At the beginning the bearings are really tight but the rod fits into them. I just used the sharp edge of the rod to remove just a tiny amount of material until the rod moves freely but still stable and without noise throug the bearings.
You are still able to use a drill, but do this on low speeds and check often to not overdo the removal of material.

title: Small PD Capture Compatible Arca Tripod Plate
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I received a lovely Peak Designs Capture camera clip for Christmas, but the tripod plate that came with it was too bulky for my small camera (a Panasonic GM5). I know an Arca style tripod plate can be made small, because I have one that fits my camera perfectly. I went about designing a smaller clip that is compatible with the PD Capture and retains Arca tripod compatibility.

This plate fits well on my GM5, and allows the battery door to open as long as the plate is mounted off-center. I designed two options; one with slots for forward/back adjustment, one with simple tapped holes.

You will need to find a tripod screw. I modeled this to use one that I already had. The thread is, of course, 1/4"-20. The post is about 7mm tall, with about 4mm of thread at the top. The head is 11mm in diameter.

NOTE: I take no responsibility for your camera equipment if you use this. My camera is very small and light, and will probably be fine, but if you suspend your camera from this plate, remember that the plate is printed in plastic and you do so at your own risk.

description.text:
This is a tiny fast blade holder for the small utility knife blades - more robust than an exacto, but not as bulky as a stanley blade.

Only takes 7 minutes to print - it holds the blade firmly and has a blade retainer.

Its a trial printing with PLA - it has quite a long 'bridge' and a 'spring' retainer - having got the dimensions sussed, I'll use the same structure for holding these blades in other projects.

Printer:

Reprap Prusa i3 2017 model (from kit)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

I printed it with PLA, it has a long bridge, with no support and needs tweaking once complete.

NOTE Print with the retainer side down - so the big flat side is done last, bridging the whole blade slot.

Cleaning

If the bridge over the void has held, nothing needs doing.

But...

The void for the blade is likely to need a bit of 'separating' if the bridge hasn't held up.

Just slipping the blade in and wiggling a bit works fine - careful separating the 'retention' blob - cut it off and the blade may not stay put. I found levering it was better than trying to cut it free.
I measured the blade and tweaked through 5 prints!

title: Laser cutting material template remixed for K40 Laser

description.text:
This is a remix of the Laser cutting materiale template by Noloxs. The Chinese K40 Laser does not have variable power control to do shading so all shaded images must be converted to halftone, so I converted the engraving test to a halftone image. I do halftone conversion in Photoshop and get good results. I am uploading it as a Corel Laser Draw file for ease of use and editing . I have set the text up as multiple level for ease of editing.

To use:
Select engrave layer from the object manager in Corel.
Expand the engrave to see the layers.
Edit text for your settings and material and notes.
Select engraving operation in Corel and set the settings for your material.
After engraving is complete select cut layer in the object manager.
Select engraving operation in Corel and set the style to cutting then change the settings for cutting your material.

description.text:
UPDATE 5/1/17 !!!! - Made the tab hole radius, tab thickness (height), and tab width (and length) customizable.

UPDATE 4/19/17 !!!! - I've added a new mirror mode to the OpenSCAD file. Mirror==2 will lay the mounts flat instead of standing them up. See "WAGO 221 mount 5C-3C-2C M2.stl" as an example.

UPDATE 2/1/17 !!!! - I originally designed the mounts using Tinkercad and only for the 5 conductor version, 221-415. I've now designed it using OpenSCAD. Its now configurable for any of the 3 versions of the WAGO 221 connectors: 221-412 (2 conductors), 221-413 (3 conductors), and 221-415 (5 conductors). You can also specify any number of those connectors and any combination of those connectors. In addition you can specify whether to do 2 back to back rows (mirror = 1) or just a single row (mirror = 0). And you can turn off the tabs if you don't want them.

I've generated a number of additional mounts for the 221-412 connectors and the 221-413 connectors. Lastly, there are STLs which include the 221-412, 221-413, and 221-415 all in a single mount.

You can of course use the OpenSCAD file to create whatever WAGO 221 mount you need and then export the STL.

1/31/17 - I have a bunch of WAGO 221-415 connectors. I like these over the 222 series because the 221 series is thinner. But... while there are a bunch of 222 series cases on Thingiverse, I couldn't find any for the 221 series. So I made my own. These are specifically for the 221-415, 5 conductor connectors. I made a version for a single 221-415 all the way up to a 3 x 2. There are mounting tabs so you can screw this down to a frame, whether it be wood or 2020 extrusions. The holes in the tabs are 4mm in diameter.

I've tested the single 221-415 and the 2 x 1. I haven't had a chance to test the others yet. A 221-415 fits well in the both of them as you can see in the photos. At least as printed on my printer. You might need to tweak the scale slightly depending on your printer. The tolerances are so tight that even a 0.2mm change will make it impossible to fit or too loose.

Uwe Rosenberg's new game for 2016, A Feast For Odin, is a sprawling monstrosity of cardboard and wood. It's a fantastic and intuitive game, but setup and takedown is a bear. Since it was so new, no one had made any inserts available for sale so I figured it was a good a time as any to buy a cheap 3d printer, build it from crappy parts, find a CAD program, learn how to use that, and make an insert.

So, here's what resulted... fifteen pieces. Basically a roll of filament (perhaps a shade more).. BUT.. the end result is also a game that takes about five minutes to setup. A game which fits back in the box well, although I put 1-1.5 cm of the punchboards back in the bottom of the box to make sure the game doesn't wobble around too much.

I printed the whole thing with .2mm layers. I used a .5 nozzle in Simplify3D laying down filament at a width of .6. I designed the walls at 2.4 mm, so a 2 line border would give me four equal passes with no infill for the basic tiles.

I hope everyone finds it as useful as I do.
